Slovenia's Information Ministry confirmed today that federal military
commanders met in March to consider ways to deal with Slovenian
dissidents.  The military blamed the dissent on a foreign-backed
conspiracy.  Slovenia's police and Communist Party disagree.

Army commanders have been increasingly critical of Slovenia's leaders,
urging them to act firmly against political dissidents.

Mladina, the Socialist Youth Organization's publication, wrote
Slovenia's Communist Party that the army planned to arrest dissidents
and use force in any resulting protest. They added that the civilian
government was not notified of the army's intentions.

The plan, blocked by Slovenia's president, was denied by the
military.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d45"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP891201-0100"
SELECTOR="H"
SUMMARIZER="K">     

Serbia cut political and economic ties with Slovenia Friday, prompting
Slovenia to charge that Serbia is attempting to "oust us from
Yugoslavia."

Earlier, police had dispersed a pro-Serbian rally in Ljubljana,
Slovenia's capital, after Slovenia banned the event.  Serbia's break
with Slovenia was in reaction to that dispersal.

Slovenia's collective presidency protested to Serbia, asserting the
rally was an attempt to unseat their leaders.

The clash demonstrates major ideological differences: Slovenia
recognizes opposition groups, while Serbia permits only the Communist
Party.

Serbia calls on Yugoslavia's Slovenian president to resign, while
Delo, the major newspaper in Ljubljana, called the action a
"declaration of war."</SUM>

<SUM
